<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FF6DFC6BFE43" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF54FF6DFED2FF5E" box="[199,305,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FED6FF6DFE68FF5E" box="[325,395,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,244,1544,1566]" captionTargetBox="[201,1378,614,1501]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[162,1426,580,1534]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Oligaeschna sirindhorni sp. nov. holotype,habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064486/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Overall broad at base, moderately constricted at S3 and thereafter moderately spindle shaped. Black with bright green or yellowish markings. S1 black with thick tuft of setae dorsally; dorsum S2 with rounded green spot anteriorly, paired transverse green dashes behind transverse carina and pair of smaller spots at base. Dorsal setae sparse. Laterally, large irregular green to yellowish antero-ventral spot extending to ventral side of auricle and smaller green medio-apical spot. Auricles pale greenish-yellow, more strongly yellow above. S3 maximally constricted at one third of its length from base; small paired green spots medially and paired transverse green spots posteriorly. Dorsal pattern on S4 similar to S3. S5 to S9 with only paired transverse green spots apically, these decreasing in size from S5 to S9. S10 entirely black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FE4DFD50FD23" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF54FE4DFE6BFE3E" box="[199,392,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Anal appendages</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FE05FE4DFDE6FE3E" box="[406,517,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1121,1143]" captionTargetBox="[232,1358,209,1057]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[208,1376,195,1101]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Oligaeschna sirindhornae sp. nov. holotype: a. synthorax lateral view; b. anal appendages, dorsal view; c anal appendages, lateralview; d. detail of penisshowing absenceof flagellum on terminal segment." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064488/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2b–c</figureCitation>
). Black. Cerci in dorsal view (
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FCC6FE4DFC45FE3E" box="[853,934,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1121,1143]" captionTargetBox="[232,1358,209,1057]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[208,1376,195,1101]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Oligaeschna sirindhornae sp. nov. holotype: a. synthorax lateral view; b. anal appendages, dorsal view; c anal appendages, lateralview; d. detail of penisshowing absenceof flagellum on terminal segment." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064488/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
) long and robust; nearly twice length of S10; with slightly sinuous outline, medially kinked in outer margin, distal half approximately an elongate oval shape with strong longitudinal ridge. In lateral view (
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FD32FE05FD12FDF6" box="[673,753,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1121,1143]" captionTargetBox="[232,1358,209,1057]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[208,1376,195,1101]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Oligaeschna sirindhornae sp. nov. holotype: a. synthorax lateral view; b. anal appendages, dorsal view; c anal appendages, lateralview; d. detail of penisshowing absenceof flagellum on terminal segment." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064488/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
) cerci rather angulate, broad anteriorly narrowing maximally at two-fifths length from base; small pointed sub-basal process present ventrally; apical three-fifths forming a narrow approximately triangular shape with vertices on the midpoint of dorsum at the corner of a ventral flange and apically; apex slightly truncated obliquely. Epiproct about half length of cerci, narrow basally and narrowing slightly further towards apex which expands narrowly to form a moderately excavated fork; in lateral view, curving smoothly upward with terminal re-curved spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FD22FEBBFCB3" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF54FD22FE47FD1E" box="[199,420,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Accessory genitalia</emphasis>
. With spine of anterior lamina small; anterior hamule slightly serrated with small spines. Penis (
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FF70FD06FED7FCFB" box="[227,308,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,244,1121,1143]" captionTargetBox="[232,1358,209,1057]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[208,1376,195,1101]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Oligaeschna sirindhornae sp. nov. holotype: a. synthorax lateral view; b. anal appendages, dorsal view; c anal appendages, lateralview; d. detail of penisshowing absenceof flagellum on terminal segment." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064488/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
) strongly curved, basal joint of (seminal vesicle) thick and with fleshy lobe. Second joint of penis as thick as posterior of basal joint, heavily folded, fleshy lobes large, heavily folded, terminating in a sharp pointed tip, no flagellum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FC92FB1DFC6E" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" box="[199,1278,871,896]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Measurements [mm]. Hw 40, abdomen without anal appendages 42, cerci ca 4.1, epiproct ca 2.1</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37219DAFFF82017FF54FC71FD2BFB4E" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FC71FCAEFBFE" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF54FC71FEA2FC4A" bold="true" box="[199,321,907,932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species distinctly differs from all other congeners by the unique shape of its cerci in both dorsal and lateral view. The nearest relatives geographically are known from Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F37F0AC1FFF82017FB22FC55FAF8FC26" box="[1201,1307,943,968]" name="Malaysia" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
. These are 
<taxonomicName id="4C6831D2FFF82017FF04FC2EFDABFC02" authority="(Foerster, 1903)" authorityName="Foerster" authorityYear="1903" baseAuthorityName="Foerster" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[151,584,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Aeshnidae" genus="Oligoaeschna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amata">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF04FC2EFE67FC02" box="[151,388,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Oligoaeschna amata</emphasis>
(Foerster, 1903)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6831D2FFF82017FD1BFC2EFBA9FC03" authority="Lieftinck, 1968" authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1968" box="[648,1098,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Aeshnidae" genus="Oligoaeschna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foliacea">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FD1BFC2EFC6AFC03" box="[648,905,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Oligoaeschna foliacea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF937A0FFF82017FC06FC2EFBA9FC03" author="Lieftinck" box="[917,1098,980,1005]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1968) A review of the genus Oligoaeschna Selys in Southeast Asia. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 111, 137 - 186." type="journal article" year="1968">Lieftinck, 1968</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in which the cerci are very dissimilar from this species (see the illustrations in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF937A0FFF82017FD45FC02FCA2FBFE" author="Orr" box="[726,833,1015,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" refString="Orr, A. G. (2005) A pocket guide: Dragonflies of Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore. Natural History Publications (Borneo), Sdn. Bhd, 125 pp." type="book" year="2005">Orr 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD74A51FFF82017FF54FBE1FD2BFB4E" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FF54FBE1FEC9FBDA" bold="true" box="[199,298,1051,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6831D2FFF82017FEA2FBE6FD86FBDB" authority="Ngiam &amp; Orr, 2017" authorityName="Ngiam &amp; Orr" authorityYear="2017" box="[305,613,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Aeshnidae" genus="Oligoaeschna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirindhornae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FEA2FBE6FD86FBDB" box="[305,613,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Oligoaeschna sirindhornae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22F2B38FFF82017FDFFFBE6FD25FBDA" box="[620,710,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B91C9643FFF82017FDFFFBE6FD25FBDA" bold="true" box="[620,710,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
was found in mixed dipterocarp forest, at a shallow stream with small boulders at the bottom of a ravine by the edge of a silviculture plantation (
<figureCitation id="135356D4FFF82017FB82FBC5FBB6FBB6" box="[1041,1109,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="3.[151,244,1980,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,211,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,211,1925]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitatwhere the holotype of O.sirindhornae sp. nov. was captured." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1064492/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="199">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It was collected in late June when the stream was dry during a period of low rainfall. The specimen was caught when it was flushed from the undergrowth and rested among a thicket of palms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
